[00:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '12 GP got some exciting new updates in the past week, integrating some brand new open-source models such as Ideogram 4, Nvidia\'s Pixel Diffusion Decoder, the Bernini video framework, and Joy AI Echo.'

[00:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In this video, we will take a quick look at all of them. Let\'s start with Ideogram 4. Looking at its project page, it becomes clear that this text-to-image model is very good at generating complex images such as posters, but it\'s also very'

[00:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'capable at generating photorealistic images. Being a 9.3 billion parameter model, it has some strong real-world knowledge and performs among some of the top closed-source models available on the market in real-world design.'

[00:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'However, in my opinion, the real strength of this model lies in its detailed prompting technique. You can use simple prompts for Ideogram, but it really begins to shine when you use prompts in JSON format. With those, you can build complex scenes by telling the'

[01:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'model exactly where to place objects, guide the lighting and aesthetics of the image, and define the background elements. You can find detailed prompting guides on the corresponding GitHub page, but'

[01:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'also directly in 12 GP. Open it up and select Ideogram 4 from the drop-down menu at the top. There are currently two model versions available, an FP8 and an FP4 version.'

[01:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The FP4 version is smaller, but I\'d still advise to go for the FP8 version. It runs fine even on my RTX 3060 with just 12 GB of VRAM. You can choose between three different'

[01:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'presets here. They differ in the amount of steps needed to generate the image. With just 12 steps, you already get very decent results, but for higher fidelity, choose the 20-step preset. 48 steps is too overpowered in my opinion, as it'

[01:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'takes over 9 minutes to generate a single image on my machine. Now for the prompt, click on the little info icon on the right to get a general idea of how this model interprets JSON format prompts.'

[02:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Don\'t worry, you don\'t need to manually write those complicated prompts. Instead, write a simple prompt describing all elements you want to see and use the prompt enhancer below. It transforms your input into the structured JSON format.'

[02:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I have prepared a little example. The starting prompt for this one is a casual photo of a polar bear wearing a royal cloak and a crown sitting on a wooden throne in a majestic castle hall. There are big windows showing a'

[02:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mountainous landscape with peaks covered in snow in the background. Medieval soldiers are standing on the left and right side of the bear. Now click on magic prompt and wait for the result. After a few seconds, the initial prompt'

[02:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'got replaced by the generated JSON format prompt. 123GP has introduced a very useful visual prompt helper tool like it\'s available in ComfyUI as well. To use it, hit the little magic wand'

[02:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'next to the info icon. A new window appears with a graphical interface of all your objects and where they should appear in the image. You can drag and drop the elements position and size to your desire. For example, I\'d like to place the polar'

[03:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bear on the throne to the center of the image and the soldiers to the left and right. To add another element, simply click'

[03:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into the canvas to create a new object. In this case, let\'s add a cat lying next to the bear. Below, you can specify general'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'properties of your image, for example, the background, aesthetics, art style, lighting, and photo details. The high-level description explains the general conception of the image. If you are ready, click on save changes and'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'close the window. When choosing the resolution, always make sure the aspect ratio matches with the one in the prompt. Let\'s go for a medium resolution in a 4x3 ratio, although the model can handle much higher resolutions. Let\'s hit'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generate and see what we get. The generation is complete and took approximately 4 minutes on my system. It\'s incredible how precise and coherent the result is. All the prompted elements got placed into the image at the desired'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'positions. It generated more soldiers than I intended, but this can be easily fixed by a more detailed prompt. This is another example I just generated. Ideogram 4 is also very capable at text rendering. So, I created this scene of a'

[04:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'woman in front of a cafe named Game of Scones. In the prompt helper tool, you can specifically choose elements to be text elements in this little box. That\'s what I did with the cafe logo and also with the little sign on the right'

[04:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'saying, "Help wanted." This image was generated in just 12 steps, by the way, and took only 2 minutes. The model can generate much more complex text renderings, such as film posters, but assembling such a prompt would take'

[04:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'too long for this video. So, feel free to experiment here. In the latest update, Wanh 2 GP also integrated the new Nvidia PID, short for pixel diffusion decoder. It is a great alternative to upscalers,'

[05:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'such as SeedVR2, but has a big advantage. Instead of decoding the image and then re-encoding and applying the upscaling process, PID unifies decoding and upsampling into one generative step, enabling workflows to generate sharp 4K'

[05:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'results in seconds by denoising directly in high-resolution pixel space. This, in theory, requires a model using a Flux VAE model, though. So, models like Flux 2 Klein 9B or Z image can make'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'use of this process. You can read about it if you select an image model in Wanh 2 GP, go to the advanced mode, and then select the post-processing tab. Here, click the little info icon next to the spatial'

[05:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'upsampling drop-down. The awesome thing is, in Wanh 2 GP, you are not limited to models that use the flux VAE decoder. You can in fact use any image model. This is described on the bottom of this window.'

[05:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'To make use of this, just upload an existing image into the gallery, select late post-processing, and then flux 2 PID upsampler. The sacrifice is a small quality loss as'

[06:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the image has to be encoded again, contrary to the previously mentioned unified approach. But in my test so far, both approaches are delivering really sharp results. However, using the unified VAE method while generating an image somehow'

[06:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'desaturates the image a lot. I hope this color instability will be fixed in a future 12GP update. Next up is a model derived from 12.2 called Bernini. This allows you to modify existing videos in many ways.'

[06:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'There\'s a ton of examples on their project page, including adding and removing objects, changing the video\'s background or perspective, modifying the style, and much, much more. It also supports content insertion and allows to'

[06:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'use reference images for multiple purposes. This comes at a cost, though. The model is very heavy and might not run on low VRAM systems despite 12GP\'s amazing memory management. I still managed to test out a few'

[07:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generations, but without reference images. At this point, you can\'t use lightning LoRAs when using a reference image, so it takes an eternity on my 3060. For this video, I wanted to change the'

[07:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'background to a mountainous landscape, and here is the result. To be honest, even at only 480p, this is a perfect result. I used the four-step text-to-video lightning LoRA, so it took 11 minutes to'

[07:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generate a 5-second video. With better hardware, like a GPU from the 50 series, you should be able to generate results much faster. This is another example. I prompted to change the scene into a snowy winter wonderland, and here is the'

[07:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'result. And as a third example, I tried something that the LTX edit anything Laura couldn\'t do at all. Remove the two'

[07:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'men walking behind the two women. And what can I say? This model is really capable of editing, the best I\'ve seen so far to be honest. With enough patience and a beefy GPU, this is a real powerhouse.'

[08:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'At the time of recording this video, 12 GP also just integrated a much smaller 12.1 based variant of the Bernini model. With just 1.3 billion parameters compared to the full 14 billion parameter model, this is supposed to run'

[08:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'faster and on lower VRAM, but with the downside of being weaker with complex tasks. Do you want me to cover it in another video? Let me know in the comments. Lastly, 12 GP also added a LTX 2.3 based model called Joy AI Echo last'

[08:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'week, which is designed to produce long videos with consistent characters and objects. It achieves that by storing audio-visual information in a memory bank, preserving character appearance and voices consistently over minute-long'

[08:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'videos. It is currently focused on text-to-video generations. However, in 12 GP, the implementation goes further than that. You can additionally insert a control video and use the character or object information from that to generate'

[08:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your video. A guide about the different commands needed to store and load memories with and without a control video can be found in the prompt help window over here. As this can be quite overwhelming to'

[09:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'begin with, you can also make use of the prompt enhancer again. Let me show you an example of how to use Joy AI without using a control video first. I created this 24-second story about a date between a man and a woman'

[09:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going wrong. It consists of four sliding windows, six seconds each. You can pause the video in order to read the full prompt, but the important parts are the commands inside the brackets. With store mem, you can save character'

[09:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or object information for later use. That\'s what I did with the first shot only showing the woman and the second shot only showing the man. In the second window, I used the command load mem to not load the previous memory of the woman. I also used new shot for a clear'

[09:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hard cut. In the third and fourth window, the memories of the man and woman get loaded by the command load mem. This led to the following result. &gt;&gt; Okay.'

[10:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Just act natural. He\'s going to love this. &gt;&gt; Almost. Got him. Stay focused, Leah. &gt;&gt; So, tell me, what are your long-term goals?'

[10:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; To beat level 42. &gt;&gt; Ugh, I should have just stayed home. &gt;&gt; Yes! Level 42 cleared! &gt;&gt; As you have seen, the characters\' identities got carried over to the'

[10:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'subsequent shots despite the scene changes in between, and that\'s the strength of Joy AI Echo. With normal LT X, the characters would very likely change midway, especially after several cuts. But the 1 2 GP integration still'

[10:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'has lots of issues. The prompted scene changes got ignored almost completely, and the lip sync in the third and fourth window is also off. I tried many more generations with variations of the prompt, but never got a really usable'

[10:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'result. So, I hope this gets improved in the near future to the point that we can get similar results as shown on the project page. Let\'s just quickly look at how it handles the memories captured from a control video. I used this 10-second'

[11:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shot of a man speaking directly to the camera. &gt;&gt; Being a chef means staying focused, no matter how stressful the day is. Always keep your eyes on your knife.'

[11:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; For the Joy memory positions, I choose to capture them at around 2 and 7 seconds. Then I loaded the captured memories with load mem and wrote a prompt. A man in his 30s with a full beard and long brown'

[11:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hair stands in a beautiful sunlit garden with a puzzled expression on his face. He\'s asking insecurely directly into the camera, "What do you mean I am a clone of myself? Am I in a matrix?" And here\'s the result.'

[11:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; What do you mean I am a clone of myself? Am I in a matrix? &gt;&gt; Again, the overall scene wasn\'t changed'

[11:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'unfortunately, but the character cloning has nevertheless worked decently. That was it for now. Lots of new stuff to explore in 1.2 GP. What do you think about the new models available? If you'

[12:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have any further questions, let me know in the comments. Like and subscribe if this was helpful and I will see you in the next video.'
